Supplementary material to Rasplus et al 2020 - RADseq phylogenomics of Ficus species

1 Content of this document

This document provides the R code to perform the analyses presented in supplementary figures FigS4C (PCA analysis of GC content for sect. Pharmacosycea vs other fig trees - Mixtiflores excluded) and FigS5 (PCA analysis of LB scores for sect. Pharmacosycea vs other fig trees).

The corresponding datasets are available in example_figureS4C.csv and example_figureS5.csv respectively.

The code has been discussed by J.-P. Rossi, J.-Y. Rasplus and A. Cruaud and written by JPR.

2 Required R packages

The R code below requires the R package ade4 (PCA) and httr (reading datasets from the Github).

To install ade4 type install.package("ade4") in the R console.

Of course, you should have installed R before (check R site here: https://cran.r-project.org/)

Note that the raw data can be read as a .csv file using the R function read.csv. If your own data come as .xls files you may need the R package gdata or something equivalent.

3 Managing raw data

3.1 Reading from data file

rm(list=ls())
library(httr)
# reading the file example_figureS4c.csv corresponding to Figure FigS4C
g <- GET(url="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/acruaud/radseq_ficus_2020/master/PCA/example_figureS4C.csv")
d<-read.csv(g$url, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = F)  #note that the field separator of the csv is "," in the example files and that empty cells (missing data) have been filled with "NA"

We check the matrix dimensions (nb columns and lines) to make sure all taxa and all loci are loaded.

dim(d)
## [1]  49 585

There are 49 rows that stand for taxa. There are 585 columns. The 2 first columns give information on taxa labels and group of taxa. The remaining 583 columns correspond to GC content of taxa for each locus.

We can check the names of the first 5 columns:

names(d)[1:5]
## [1] "class"       "taxa_labels" "loci100"     "loci101"     "loci102"
head(d)[1:5, 1:5]
##   class                   taxa_labels loci100 loci101 loci102
## 1     1     F_insipida_JRAS06137_0001   0.460   0.469   0.363
## 2     1  F_gigantosyce_JRAS06146_0001   0.469   0.478   0.363
## 3     1 F_crassivenosa_JRAS06891_0001      NA   0.478   0.363
## 4     1    F_carchiana_JRAS06894_0001   0.469   0.478   0.363
## 5     1   F_torresiana_JRAS06908_0001   0.460   0.478   0.363

We can list the different classes (= groups of taxa) to make sure data have been loaded correctly:

unique(d$class)
## [1] 1 2

Classes are groups of species. When the dataset includes more than 2 classes (=groups), unnecessary rows can be removed. Here or you may prefer to use your usual spreadsheet. In this example, Mixtiflores have been removed from the data set; fig trees belonging to sect Pharmacosycea are in class (=group) 1 while other fig trees are in class (=group) 2.

3.2 Dealing with NA data

Some cells of the data.frame might contain NA when there is no sequence for the locus (missing values).

Here we can test whether our data set contains missing data calculate the number of loci that have missing values

isna.col <- apply(X=d[,-c(1,2)], MARGIN=2, FUN=function(x) any(is.na(x)))
any(isna.col==TRUE)
## [1] TRUE

and calculate the number of loci for which we have missing data.

length(which(isna.col==TRUE))
## [1] 579

This is huge given that NAs are not allowed in PCA ! The first solution is to remove either the locus or the species. However, as most data sets are patchy like here, this solution will often result in the complete deletion of the data.frame. Thus, we decided to replace NA values by the mean value of all available observations of the corresponding locus following Dray & Josse (2015).

So, we create a function to do the job:

NAtomean <- function(x) {x[which(is.na(x)==TRUE)] <- mean(x, na.rm=TRUE) ; return(x)}

And we use the function to create a new matrix (d) in which NAs have been replaced by the mean value of all available observations of the corresponding locus

labels <- d[,c(1,2)] ; d <- d[,-c(1,2)]
groups <- factor(labels[,1])
d <- data.frame(apply(X=d, MARGIN=2, FUN=NAtomean))

and check the dimensions of the new matrix

dim(d)
## [1]  49 583

4 Data analysis using the PCA

4.1 Initial (full) PCA

We first perform a first PCA using the full dataset.

library(ade4)
pca <- dudi.pca(d, scannf = F, nf = 5)

The eigenvalues (i.e.the variance of the species scores upon the principal axes) are given by:

barplot(height=100*pca$eig/sum(pca$eig), xlab="rank", ylab="eigenvalues (%)")

The species scores upon the first two axes can be represented as follows:

s.class(dfxy=pca$li, fac=groups, col=c("black", "red"), sub="PCA of the full dataset")

In this plot, species belonging to sect. Pharmacosycea = group 1 are in black and other fig trees = group 2 are in red.

Note that you may export graphs with the pdf function of R. To export the previous graph (PCA on the complete data set) you should use something like below (uncomment the cmd to make it work - i.e remove the #). A file named PCA_complete_dataset.pdf will be created in your current directory.

#pdf(file="PCA_complete_dataset.pdf")
#s.class(dfxy=pca$li, fac=groups, col=c("black", "red"), sub="PCA of the full dataset")
#dev.off()

Another way to display the same information as the previous graph is:

s.label(dfxy=pca$li, xax = 1, yax = 2, label=row.names(d), sub="PCA of the full dataset")

Here, labels are numbers corresponding to species but species name could be used instead.

4.2 PCAs of thinned datasets

The idea is to explore how removing the loci that have the highest correlation with the first principal component (i.e.axis) decreases the distance between groups (classes) 1 and 2. This means that we need to sort the loci in function of their correlation (i.e.their score) upon the first axis of the PCA.

For that purpose we create a new data.frame and store the scores of the loci that are given in the object pca$co.

genes.df <- data.frame(names(d))
genes.df[,1] <- as.character(genes.df[,1])
genes.df$score.pc1 <- pca$co[,1]
names(genes.df) <- c("loci", "pc1")
head(genes.df)
##      loci        pc1
## 1 loci100  0.1735608
## 2 loci101 -0.7538363
## 3 loci102  0.2447913
## 4 loci103  0.4239923
## 5 loci104  0.3533326
## 6 loci105  0.2158756
genes.df.ordered <- genes.df[order(-genes.df[,2]), ]
head(genes.df.ordered) 
##        loci       pc1
## 367 loci430 0.8738155
## 103 loci193 0.8003328
## 136 loci222 0.7597904
## 567  loci85 0.7459044
## 238 loci314 0.7457877
## 580  loci97 0.7416996

4.3 How many iterations?

Removing the loci will be done in an iteratuve way. Each iteration corresponds to the PCA of a thinned dataset. The first thinned dataset is the original dataset minus the locus displaying the highest correlation with the first component of the full PCA. In the second iteration, the two loci showing the highest correlation with the first components are removed. And so on.

In this example, the maximum number of iterations is fixed to 550. Note that it is better to keep enough loci in the last PCA to make the analysis meaningfull.

N <- 550

4.4 PCAs on thinned datasets

The code below performes the 550 PCAs with the corresponding thinned datasets.

lim <- 1 ; increm <- 1
list_pca <- vector("list", length=N+1)
list_pca[[1]] <- dudi.pca(d, scannf = F, nf = 5) # initial pca (i.e. with full dataset)

for(i in 1:(N)){
  retir <- genes.df.ordered[1:lim,1]
  m <- match(retir, names(d))
  temp <- d[,-m]
  list_pca[[i+1]] <- dudi.pca(temp, scannf = F, nf = 5)
  lim <- lim+increm
  }

4.5 Computing inter-group distance along PCA axis 1

The PCAs are stored in the list list_pca and can be used to compute the average difference between the scores of the two groups along the first axis as follows:

dist.vec <- rep(NA, times=length(list_pca))

for(i in 1:length(list_pca)){
  w1 <- which(groups==levels(groups)[1])
  w2 <- which(groups==levels(groups)[2])
  pc1_g1 <- list_pca[[i]]$li[w1,1]
  pc1_g2 <- list_pca[[i]]$li[w2,1]
  diff <- mean(pc1_g1) - mean(pc1_g2)
  dist.vec[i] <- abs(diff)
  }

We can plot the changes in the absolute value of the average euclidean distance separating the two groups along the first axis of the PCA in function of number of loci that were removed:

plot(1:length(list_pca), abs(dist.vec), type="b", cex=0.1, xlab="iteration", ylab="Average distance between groups")

4.6 Assessing statistical significance

The next step is to assess for which iteration the distance becomes non significant from a statistical viewpoint. Here we adopted a simple approach based on the Wilcoxon test but other tests could be used:

list_pca_tests <- vector("list", length=N+1)

for(i in 1:length(list_pca)){
  test <- wilcox.test(list_pca[[i]]$li[,1]~groups)
  list_pca_tests[[i]] <- test
  }

The function unlist() allows to store the p-values in a vector:

p.values <- unlist(lapply(X=list_pca_tests, FUN=function(x) return(x$p.value)))
#p.values

Which p-values are significant at the 5% threshold? Significant and non-significant values are printed in red and grey respectively.

ws <- which(p.values < 0.05) ; wns <- which(p.values >= 0.05)
dtemp <- data.frame(iteration=1:length(list_pca), dist=dist.vec)

plot(dtemp$iteration, dtemp$dist, type="n", xlab="iteration", ylab="Average distance between groups")
points(dtemp$iteration[ws], dtemp$dist[ws], type="p", cex=0.2, col="red")
points(dtemp$iteration[wns], dtemp$dist[wns], type="p", cex=0.1, col="grey")

Here we see that all values are significant, which means that scores of the two groups on pc1 are always statistically different.

5.2 data.frame with full results of the iteration process

Based on the former data.frame a second output is created with the name of the removed locus and its score upon axis 1 in the initial PCA with full dataset, the probability level, the iteration number and the distance separating the groups.

iteration.out <- genes.df.ordered[1:N,]
iteration.out$pvalue_wilcoxon <- p.values[-1] # remove the value corresponding to the full PCA
iteration.out$iteration <- 1:N

names(iteration.out) <- c("removed_loci", "score_pc1", "pvalue_wilcoxon", "iteration")

ws <- which(iteration.out$pvalue_wilcoxon < 0.05)
wns <- which(iteration.out$pvalue_wilcoxon >= 0.05)
iteration.out$significance <- rep(NA, times=dim(iteration.out)[1])
iteration.out$significance[ws] <- "s"
iteration.out$significance[wns] <- "ns"
iteration.out$distance <- dist.vec[-1] # remove the value corresponding to the full PCA
head(iteration.out)

6 Additional graphical outputs

6.1 Score of first N loci upon the first axis of the full PCA

The code below allows to plot the score of the loci upon the first axis of the full PCA sorted in descending order with colors showing the level of probability: loci are incrementally removed and the statistical significance of the difference between the groups is assessed at each step. Significant differences are printed in red while non-significant values are printed in black.

plot(iteration.out$iteration, iteration.out$score_pc1, type="n", xlab="iteration", ylab="score upon PCA axis 1")
points(iteration.out$iteration[ws], iteration.out$score_pc1[ws], type="h", cex=0.2, col="red")
points(iteration.out$iteration[wns], iteration.out$score_pc1[wns], type="h", cex=0.2, col="grey")

6.2 Scatterplot of species scores for any PCA

Select one of the N PCA on thinned dataset and plot the species upon the first two principal axes.

i <- 5     #here we choose iteration 5
s.class(dfxy=list_pca[[i]]$li, fac=groups, col=c("black", "red"), sub=paste("PCA iteration ", i, sep=""))

7 Additional example corresponding to the figure FigS5

In this example, fig trees belonging to sect. Pharmacosycea are in group 2 (red) and all other fig trees are in group 1 (black). The analysed properties is the LB score for each locus of the mergeR1R2 data set. 500 iterative PCAs are performed. We can see on the resulting plots that scores of the two groups on pc1 are not always statistically different.
